{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"655d8657-9267-4296-8346-c6abb9e171d6","content":"Since you already have the dump file, you're past the collection phase. Here's how to analyze it:\n\n**Using `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for OOM issues) |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch threads before `clrstack` |\n\n**Quick workflow:**\n1. Run `pe` first — it often reveals the crashing exception and stack trace immediately.\n2. Use `clrthreads` → `setthread` → `clrstack` to inspect other threads.\n\n**Alternatives:** You can also use **lldb** (Linux/macOS) with the SOS plugin, or **WinDbg** (Windows) for deeper native-level analysis.\n\nThe `dump-collect` skill I have available is only for *capturing* dumps — not analyzing them. Let me know if you need help with any specific step!","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d8339c0b-2aef-43a3-b53c-065d7b6867ce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description says it's for configuring and collecting crash dumps, and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo the skill is not appropriate here. I should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":420,"requestId":"981F:81F2F:7A1DF2C:86CE41A:69F407B8"},"id":"efcf03ec-cbac-4b16-8b18-8dcd45947bc4","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:54:11.526Z","parentId":"0a7599be-2890-4cea-a196-ae416ab2136a"}
